snippet.textDisplay:
i never knew just how good a general robert e lee was. i mean i always knew that pretty much the nobody the north had could be his match but every thing i was taught said that grant was his match. in reality though if you look at the casualty numbers even grant was not a match for lee as despite outnumbering him in nearly every battle grant took significantly more casualties than lee which especially at that time said a lot since the rifles were not very accurate meaning the more people you had the more chance you had to land a shot. i mean lee took the wrong side but you have to respect that level of competence. the dude nearly single handily beat the entire northern army despite being outnumbered 3 to 1 and only lost in the end because the north gave up on beating him with superior strategy and decided to just pummel him with wave after wave of there infantry.


also because i feel like lee gets a way worse rap than he deserves due to historically illiterate individuals one thing not alot of people know is lee was actually opposed to slavery and deemed it a moral and political evil. he decided to join the southern states due to his extreme loyalty towards his home state and saw the civil war as being due to an overreaching government violating state rights. i mean the way we are taught about the civil war is always way to oversimplified. its actually sorta ironic that a youtube channel literally named oversimplified actually delves deeper into it than most history classes.


i mean heck i did not even know about how the difference in level of industrialization contributed to the difference in attitudes towards slavery and the need of it among the northern and southern states untill i learned about how industrialization happened mostly in northern states whilst southern states remain relatively un industrialized even today and then connected the dots myself. i mean maybe i just had a bad teacher but the way i see most people talk about the civil war as a purely white and black issue it seems to me that its more widespread a problem then just one bad teacher.
